Part 2

Dr. Sen was sitting at the corner wooden table of the hospital visitor's room. She was fifty, perhaps fifty-two years old, wearing a simple silk saree that had the dull grey color of river silt. 

She had three folders placed neatly on the table, their brown cardboard covers held together by thin, red cotton strings.

"I expected you earlier, Dr. Tripathy," she said, looking up as he walked in.

Adarsh sat in the wooden chair across from her, resting his hands on the table. "The morning shift took some time to transition," he said.

"Sarita brought him to my clinic in Shobhabazar in 2016," she said, opening the first folder. "He had been found sitting in the Alipore garage, staring at the empty silver sedan for eight hours without moving."

Adarsh looked at the papers inside the folder. The notes were written in a quick, clinical hand, with dates and observations covering the margins.

"He told me about Rehman," she said. "He described the canvas bag, the rusted zip, the way the boy painted the kitchen, even his Odia accent. He said the boy had Ira's eyes."

"Ira," Adarsh said, his voice quiet.

"He carried her memory like a stone in his shoe," she said. "Every step hurt, but he had stopped trying to shake it out."

She turned a page, the paper making a dry, sharp rustle in the quiet room. 

"The yellow envelope was real," she said. "But it was only a municipal tax receipt. Vikram needed a reason to let the boy in. So his split mind read Ira's name on the cheap yellow paper."

"Why did he need the projection?" Adarsh asked.

"Because he was tired of the split," she said, looking out through the window at the hospital parking lot. "One half of him had built the fourteen hundred crore. The other half had left the anatomy lab in ninety-six, leaving a textbook half-underlined. He wanted the well, but the tycoon in him couldn't stop building."

She tapped the brown folder with her finger. 

"Rehman was the alternate choice. The boy who could buy the silver sedan, fly to Geneva, and run the business, while Vikram slept on the wooden bench in Bagbazar. Rehman was the one who could shout at him on the terrace."

"The terrace," Adarsh said. "The candle and the sun."

"It was Vikram's own voice," she said, looking at him. "He had given the entire empire to Rohan. He had walked away. But even in Bagbazar, the local MLA still called him *Ahuja saab*. He couldn't escape the name. He was guilty that his legacy followed him."

She closed the folder. 

"The real Ira Sen appearing at the press meet broke the split. The moment she said she never had a son, the alternate choice had to end. Rehman had to disappear."

"Did Vikram know?" Adarsh asked.

"He knew," she said. "He told me he signed the CEO transfer with a blue blur because the space for the second name was blank. He said: *I wanted to give the pen to Rehman. But Rehman had no hand to take it.*"

Then she set the files back down on the table, as if she had remembered something.

"He told me one other thing," she said. "He told it to me not as a fact, but as a question he couldn't resolve."

She looked at the window. "During the year his father's condition first became serious—1996—there was a formal dinner at the house. Some supplier's anniversary, food on the good plates, people Vikram didn't know. Halfway through the meal, someone handed Binay a phone. He took the call. He came back to the table very quietly and said nothing to anyone. But his face had gone completely still."

"What had happened?" Adarsh asked.

"His oldest brother had died that evening. The one in Cuttack."

"I didn't know Binay had a brother."

"Most people didn't. They were estranged." She turned her eyes from the window. "But here is the thing Vikram couldn't reconcile. His father sat back down at the dinner table, picked up the gulab jamun they had just been served, and put it in his mouth. Ate it completely. Then he wiped his hands on the cloth napkin and continued the dinner."

Adarsh said nothing.

"Vikram asked me: *Is it possible to swallow sweetness like poison? Or was he swallowing the news in small pieces, the way the stomach accepts what the mind cannot?* He said he watched his father's throat move as he swallowed the jamun, and he never forgot the sound of it." She paused. "I didn't have a clinical answer for that. I still don't."

She opened the second folder briefly, turned a page. "He also spoke at length about Ira. About why he had wanted her specifically, not merely someone like her."

"He spoke about it directly?" Adarsh asked.

"With considerable clarity, actually." She turned the page back. "He said—and I am quoting from my notes—'I did not chase her because she was beautiful, though she was. I chased her because I wanted to know what everything looked like from behind her eyes. She had a way of seeing the same event I had seen and finding in it something I had entirely missed. I wanted that perspective. I thought if I was close enough to her, some of it would transfer. It never does. It never has, with anyone. But the illusion that it might—that is the thing we are really chasing when we chase someone. Not them. The version of the world that lives inside them.'"

She closed the folder.

"You agree?" Adarsh asked.

"I find it more accurate than most things men say about why they loved someone," she said, without inflection.

She was quiet for a moment, looking at the brown cardboard covers.

"The last thing he said to me about the business years," she continued, "was this. He said: 'When I was building the company, I enjoyed it the way you enjoy arriving. The destination was always ahead. When I was building the shelter, I enjoyed it the way you enjoy walking. Every day was the thing, not the end of the thing.' He said: 'I have never understood people who chase money. They are always looking at the target. They cannot see the road. People who chase feeling are looking at the road. The target doesn't matter to them, which is why they usually don't find it either.' He smiled when he said that. It was a slow smile, the kind that seemed to have travelled a long way before it reached his face.

She tied the red string around the cardboard folder, the knot tight, neat, and final.

"His case was simple, Dr. Tripathy. Some minds break because they are weak. His broke because it was too honest to keep the palace and the well at the same time."

She looked at him before picking up the files. "His smiles were transparent," she said. "But his tears... they had no color."

Adarsh sat in the wooden chair, silent. The visitor's room was completely quiet now. 

The lawyer's deeds were in Dalhousie Square, the Alipore house was locked, and the factory compound gates in Nandyal were opening and closing. Somewhere, near the edge of a coffee estate he had never returned to, a fire had probably gone cold. He had never thanked the man who lit it. But the case file on the table was the only thing that had his friend's name written on the cover.

"Thank you, doctor," Adarsh said.

She picked up the folders and left. Her leather sandals made a quiet, clicking sound against the corridor floor, fading away until only the scratching sound of the old ceiling fan remained in the room.

[End of Part 2]
